names.fullForm: Makkūdī, ʻAbd al-Raḥmān ibn ʻAlī, d. 1404 or 5
Ibn Mālik, Muḥammad ibn ʻAbd Allāh, d. 1274

descriptiveMetadata.abstract: This manuscript contains al-Makkūdī (d. 1404)'s commentary on one of the most popular Arabic grammatical works, the Alfīyah of Ibn Malik (d. 1274). The exceptional importance of this manuscript resides in the fact that it has preserved marginalia and commentaries written by its owner, Thomas Erpenius, Dutch Orientalist and author of the first scientific grammar of Arabic written in Europe. The Arabic text of al-Makkūdī is interleaved with folios containing Erpenius annotations, which provide important information about the way Arabic was studied in Modern Europe, and also about Erpenius' relationship with the Morisco Aḥmad ibn Qāsim al-Ḥājarī , with whom he read al-Makkūdī's work.
subject: Language - Grammar - Early Works to 1800
notes: Commentary on the Alfīyah of Ibn Mālik, Muḥammad ibn ʻAbd Allāh, d. 1274.
Contains copious notes in Latin and Arabic by Thomas Erpenius 1584-1624. A table of contents has been added in a later period.
ownership: Bought from the widow of Thomas Erpenius (1584-1624) in 1632.
script: Main text in Maghribi script in brown ink. Marginal notes in European nask, brown ink.
